{"tid":2237840,"cid":18,"subCid":0,"title":"數學問題","createTime":"2020-10-10T15:09:51.000Z","updateTime":"2020-10-11T03:55:25.000Z","uid":21993,"like":0,"dislike":6,"uniUserReply":4,"replies":[{"pid":"f9ba54b47736969708924c7fd08118de79e5cd7d","tid":2237840,"uid":21993,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2020-10-10T15:09:51.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"https://na.cx/i/TP7sXZq.png\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2FTP7sXZq.png&h=353ab812&s={SIZE}\" /><img src=\"https://na.cx/i/QYzfnq7.png\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2FQYzfnq7.png&h=cdda276b&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n有無ching幫到手<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/hoho.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"5ba0128a31a85e18328524f942e59d21a6ff8544","tid":2237840,"uid":136590,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-10-10T15:33:49.000Z","msg":"Hint for A1.5 (a) <br />\nNote that \\sum_{n = 0}^{\\infty} a_n = \\exp(10^6) , i.e. the series converges<br />\n=&gt; the partial sums also converges to the same limit"},{"pid":"cb7b96248914d668f8c54555d570bb01fafccd23","tid":2237840,"uid":351368,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"quote":{"pid":"f9ba54b47736969708924c7fd08118de79e5cd7d","tid":2237840,"uid":21993,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2020-10-10T15:09:51.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"https://na.cx/i/TP7sXZq.png\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2FTP7sXZq.png&h=353ab812&s={SIZE}\" /><img src=\"https://na.cx/i/QYzfnq7.png\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2FQYzfnq7.png&h=cdda276b&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\n有無ching幫到手<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/hoho.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-10-10T16:07:40.000Z","msg":"1.6 hint: given epsilon&gt;0, there exists N_e s.t. |a_n-L|&lt;epsilon, you split the sum into 2 parts: summand with index less than N_e or greater than N_e."},{"pid":"578f5cc9b6d7099143c4fcc9b72509cae2248d67","tid":2237840,"uid":201319,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-10-11T03:55:25.000Z","msg":"A1.5) Try to estimate a lower bound on n!. In fact n! is of order n^{\\Theta(n)}. For the upper bound it is easy to see n! &lt;= n^n (why?). For the lower bound, you can get n! &gt;= (n/2)^{n/2} in a line (how?), or a tighter lower bound n! &gt;= (n/e)^n by looking at the function e^x at some x (how?). With these lower bounds, both parts are immediate."}]}